March is Endometriosis Awareness Month so i’m sharing a look into my egg freezing journey a couple years ago. Contrary to what I had heard and made up in my mind, it was far from the experience it’s been painted as. When I was diagnosed with endo back in 2015 I was told to freeze my eggs but was too afraid it would hit my mind/body/spirit too hard with the hormones. If i’m honest, I was sure I’d get fat, lose control my skin and have depression/anxiety through the roof. So I put it off. For YEARS. Until a few yrs ago when I knew my marriage was over - and this was clearly top priority. I froze my eggs at the least ideal time - in Covid, while going through a divorce. And yet, was filled with an immense amount of joy. Comfort and empowerment, but most of all- the gift of deeply seeing what I was capable of, physically and emotionally bc I made a commitment to myself to reframe my narrative around it. I made a funny playlist (which I’ll happily share), filmed myself doing every shot so I felt safe and could show doctors what I did if anything went wrong, had FT with friends lined up for after if I felt like company. People like @mrbuggy @marisa.g.ramirez @shelleyhennig who I knew would help me maintain the humor in it all. The experience was not without challenges, but the strength I gained from them only furthered my connection to myself. 

Freezing your eggs, (or anything seemingly daunting for that matter) doesn’t have to be anything more than what you choose to make it. 

This song “I am Not Afraid” by @gflip was my MF ANTHEM - feel free to borrow it for your own. 

#endometriosisawarenessmonth2024 #endometriosis #endowarrior #iamnotafraid

After 30 days, 30 protein shakes, 25+ gallons of water, 65+ meals, 56 eggs & no cheat days, i am finished. I gave myself a month to go hard and not make any excuses. Worked out every day, stuck to a strict diet and powered through all the mental/physical fatigue and bullshit tasteless meals. No alcohol, no soda, no fast food, limited sugar intake & 1 gallon/water daily.

Gained around 4 lbs. of muscle and endless amounts of mental clarity. Getting in the gym and throwing my headphones on, became one of my favorite parts of the day. 

First pic is day 1 after breakfast - 168.0 lbs. 

2nd pic is day 30 before post-workout shake/meal - 171.6 lbs.

I want to do this again, but for now… McDonalds.

Ramadan training tips 🤍 

some things that have helped me over the past year, hope these help you 🫶🏼 

1. Intention - thinking of moving your body as a form of gratitude, this will only get you closer to faith because you’re doing it as an act of “worship” by showing gratitude. It’ll give you a push on the days you aren’t feeling motivated. 

2. Plan and prepare- Personally I think there’s 3 best times to train at, I don’t recommend fasted workouts. I personally feel like 

(Before morning prayer) 
(At the time of breaking fast) 
(After you’ve broken your fast & food has digested) 

These are the best in my opinion 

3. Training styles - Ramadan guides launch Tmro @upliftyouofficial for gym & home, beginner and advanced. 

The best approach to training during Ramadan is low intensity workouts. Our goal is to maintain as much muscle as possible. Low sets, low reps, increase rest periods, and you shouldn’t be in the gym for longer than an hour. If you need a structure to help you maintain and reach your goals, guides will be 25% off tomorrow!! Excited for us to train together 🤍 

4. Nutrition - lots of fiber, greens and protein. & HYDRATION Balance is amazing but sometimes we tend to give into our cravings & over eat to the point where we’re so stuffed and we don’t feel like doing anything. Remember quality> quantity. This will make you feel so much better during the day when you are fasting bc you’re fueling your body with nutritional meals. 80/20 rule is the best. 80% nutritional meals and 20% of giving into your cravings 🫶🏼

5. Rest - can’t stress this one enough. Plan proper rest times in your routine and stick to it!! You’ll need all the rest you can get otherwise you won’t have energy to do anything. 

Let me know if this helps you ❤️

Pistachio Protein bars 🌱

Ingredients: 

- About a handful of dates (pitted) , blended into a slushy consistency = 1 cup 
- 3/4c of pistachios chopped 
- 1/3c peanut butter 
- 1 scoop of @bloomsupps vanilla whey protein powder 
- 1/2c of pure maple syrup 
- Couple squirts of honey 
- 1 cup of chocolate chips 
- 1 tbsp coconut oil 
- 1 cup of oats

How to 
1. start off by crushing your pistachios
2. Add your dates to a blender until you get a thick consistency, make sure you remove the pit from the dates and add water if it’s not mixing well 
3. Add dates to a bowl, add in vanilla whey protein powder, pistachios, peanut butter, maple syrup and honey 
4. Mix 
5. Add in your granola and 1/4 of the chocolate chips. Set aside the remainder of the chocolate chips 
6. Add parchment paper to an 8x8 pan with parchment paper 
7. Mix your coconut oil (make sure it’s solid) with the remaining chocolate chips - microwave for 15 seconds and stir, pop it back in for another 15 seconds, stir, and repeat this process until the chocolate is completely melted 
8. Add the melted chocolate evenly onto the granola bars 
9. Pop in the fridge overnight until the bars have hardened, don’t take out too soon otherwise they’ll be sticky 

Hope you enjoy🤍🤍

Tom Kha Gai soup - this was honestly so good, I followed a recipe from a cookbook so here’s the exact one : 

Ingredients: 
What I eat in a day 

-2 tablespoons extra virgin olive oil
-½ cup finely diced shallots
- salt and pepper
-1 piece fresh ginger
-2 garlic cloves, minced
-1 can unsweetened full-fat coconut milk
-1 cup low-sodium chicken broth
-2 tablespoons fish sauce
-Grated zest of 1 lime 
-1 tablespoon brown or coconut sugar
-2 to 3 bird’s eye chiles
-¼ teaspoon ground coriander
-2 stalks of lemongrass smashed
-2 pounds boneless, skinless chicken thighs trimmed and thinly sliced
-1 cup sliced white mushrooms 
-¼ cup fresh cilantro leaves

How to:
In a large pot or Dutch oven, heat the olive oil over medium heat.
Add the shallot and a pinch each of salt and pepper. Cook until the shallots are tender, 2 to 3 minutes. Add the ginger and garlic and cook until fragrant, being careful not to burn, 1 more minute.
Add the coconut milk, chicken broth, fish sauce, lime zest, lime juice, coconut sugar, chiles, and coriander. Stir to combine, then add the lemongrass. Bring the soup to a gentle simmer.
Add the sliced chicken and simmer until the chicken is just cooked through, 5 to 6 minutes. Add the mushrooms and simmer for another 3 minutes. Stir in the cilantro and season with salt to taste.
Remove and discard the lemongrass, if desired (I usually just choose to eat around it). Top with the cilantro and serve with lime wedges.

Enjoy🤍

Last week was national hijab day…. 

Dear hijab (headscarf), It’s been 9 months since I made the decision to wear you for the rest of my life. It was probably the hardest decision I’ve ever made, but sometimes in life the hardest decisions always come with the greatest reward.  Thank you for helping find the true beauty within me, to love myself for who I am instead of constantly relying on my looks to give me self validation. Not only have you taught me to focus on my inner beauty, but you’ve allowed me to get one step closer to God. You also taught me that the hijab doesn’t only mean modesty. Yes covering my hair, but also watching the way I speak, how I treat others, being kind & respectful. I’m still a work in progress but I’m trying every day. I wish you’d understand how free I feel. I thank you for helping me find true self love. I thank you for allowing me to give other women the courage to put on the hijab and get closer to modesty. I thank you for giving me opportunities to help women feel secure in the gym with the hijab as well.

The best decision I’ve ever made in my life, and I thank everyone who has supported me throughout this journey. Sending you so much love always ❤️

READ THE CAPTION!!!

1. Imagine going to the gym or getting up and moving your body every single day for 1 year straight. The tolerance you’d build will only make you stronger, and not only that the impact to your mental health will be phenomenal. A habit such as 1 hour of movement could be in the gym, yoga, walking, running, anything that requires you putting yourself through something challenging every day that you may not want to do. You’ll feel the impact 1 week in, and you will become addicted. 

2. EVOLUTION ALWAYS. You can never have too much knowledge, self educating daily is so so important as you’re growing into the better version of you.

3. Never underestimate the power of prayer & meditation. Taking the time to practice gratitude. We all struggle with anxiety and the fear of the “uncertainty” . That is why Sitting in silence with your thoughts, and confronting your anxiety will be a consistent habit in your routine that will pick you up and keep you going even on the hard days. 

4. Starting your day with the hardest task first. Sometimes we create a long to do list and we end up getting nothing done. When you set your to do list, or daily schedule. You should always have 2-3 things that are priority. Start with the hardest thing first and Do not allow procrastination and distractions, you will see so much more progress when you start doing this.

5. Overly scrolling on social media. The effect of social media can be detrimental to your mind. Comparison, not feeling good enough, feeling like you’re not in the right place in life. As a creator I believe that consuming certain types of content is beneficial, but there’s some content out there that can do more harm than good. Set daily time limits, and hold yourself accountable. This one thing is so impactful that it could be holding you back from all your goals.

Journaling 🤍 

Over the past 3 years I’ve been consistently journaling. I’ve tried many different ways but my favorite seems to be this style. 

Sticking to journaling can be hard until you make it a continuous habit, try different times to see what you like! There’s journaling in the morning, in the middle of the day, or even reflective journaling at night. 

My guided journaling at night consists of similar questions 

1. Affirmations for the night 
2. What went well 
3. What to improve on 
4. Thoughts and feelings

INGREDIENTS : 

For the soup cut 

-1 whole white onion

Buffalo chicken sandwich recipe:

Ingredients
• 2 boneless, skinless chicken breasts,
cut in half
• 1/3 cup all-purpose flour 
1/4 cup cornstarch
-1 1/2 tsp each garlic powder, onion
powder, and paprika
-1/2 tsp kosher salt
-1/2 tsp freshly ground pepper
-1/4 c Frank’s Wing Sauce
-1 1/2 tbsp almond milk 
-1 large egg
-oil cooking spray
-1 cup coleslaw mix
-2-3 tbsp Light Ranch Dressing

How: 

1. Pound the chicken breasts out to even thickness. Pat chicken very dry with paper towels.
2. In one bowl, mix together flour, cornstarch, and seasonings. In another bowl, whisk together egg and 2 tbsp Frank’s Wing Sauce.  
3. Coat chicken in egg mixture and then into seasoned flour mixture. Shake off all of the excess flour. 

4. Air fry on 400 for 11-20 min depending on thickness or cook on pan (what I did bc my air fryer broke, and put a 1-2 inch layer of oil and fry the chicken on med heat, be careful of burning the chicken)  
Pair with bread of choice, cole slaw mix + ranch 

Dinner: Stir fry + coconut rice 

Stir fry Sauce: 
•3 tbsp soy sauce
•1/2 tbsp mirin
•1-2 tbsp sugar
•2 tsp minced garlic
•pepper
•2 tsp corn starch
•3 tbsp water

Tofu:
1 block of Firm tofu, pressed with a paper towel, 1 tbsp corn starch, Salt, pepper and paprika to taste

Veggies:
•1 of each red, yellow, and orange bell pepper sliced 
•1 head bok choy, halved
•1/2 cup broccoli florets
•1/2 red onion, sliced
•1 shallot, sliced
•1 tbsp minced ginger
•1 green onion, for topping
•1/2 cup peanuts

How: 
1. Add sauce ingredients together 
2. Cook tofu on med heat until golden 
3. Add ginger, shallot, red onion with sesame oil to a pan and cook until halfway 
4. Add in rest of veggies (wait to add in the bok choy bc it cooks super fast) 
5. After veggies are cooked add in tofu + sauce 
6. Add your bok choy in + any chili sauce you may like, I added chili oil for more spice 

Pair together w coconut rice and enjoy :)

MORE INFO IN THE CAPTION🤍

1:  Prioritize form first 

Prioritizing form over weight to be specific. Sometimes ego lifting gets the best of us and we want to lift heavy weight before even mastering the movement / or getting the form down. To avoid any injuries, and to make this journey long term, patience is key and practicing the form with little to no weight first will help you achieve the results you want to see. Once you’ve mastered down the form, don’t be afraid to add weight or work on progressive overload.

2. Eat enough protein: 

Eating enough protein is going to help restore muscle fibers + helping you gain muscle mass. But not only protein… Whole Foods (nutritional meals) will also help play a role in how you perform, recovery and energy levels when training in the gym. Make nutrition a priority but don’t think you have to cut out all the foods you love, balance is key. 

3. Sleep is vital for recovery: 

 Getting ENOUGH sleep. When were sleeping our body releases a hormone (HGH) that helps MASSIVELY when repairing & growing muscle.

4. Mobility & warmup is a non negotiable: 

Emphasis on non negotiable. The key to longevity is properly taking care of our joints / muscles. AND the key to avoid muscle injuries is also by warming up and prioritizing mobility. Coming from someone who used to just jump straight into their workouts, after dealing with so many minor / major injuries… the 15 minute dynamic warmup before my lift will forever be worth it. 
Regarding mobility - There’s all types (Ex. hip mobility, ankle mobility, wrist mobility, ) working on mobility is not only going to help with form but it’s going to help with flexibility, and make training so much more efficient for you.

5.Don’t be afraid to switch things up: 

everyone’s bodies respond differently to certain styles of training.  You might get into lifting and think “this isn’t for me”, but there’s so many different styles of lifting, different exercises, different tempos, different rest periods, you name it. Don’t get discouraged by one style of training and think that in order for you to get to your goal you have to do what “everyone else” is doing. 

Hope these tips helped 🫶🏼

Playing the kashakas is harder than it looks! 🇸🇳 #LoveAfrica #Dakar #GoréeIsland #Senegal

Dakar is a city with over 300 miles of coastline, which contributes to the unique culture of the people who live here. Teranga has always guided the Senegalese way of life and is instilled into each generation at an early age, giving the city its super-welcoming vibe. These are just a few of the people who welcomed me with open arms during my visit...
:
Photo 2 - This is Isseu Diop, owner of Mburu Bakery. She is taking the French heritage of baking and infusing it with a more Senegalese perspective. Try her fonio bread, for example, or her pastries made with bissap or ditakh!
:
Photo 3, 4 & 5 - I met Professor Ousman Sene at the Massalikoul Jinaan Mosque, the largest mosque in West Africa. Majority of Senegalese identify as Muslim, so they turned to each other to raise the funds to build this Moroccan-inspired house of worship. 
:
Photo 6 - Chef Pierre Thiam is the Signature Chef at Dakar Pullman Teranga. He is a culinary ambassador who has contributed to bringing West African cuisine to the attention of the fine dining world. In Dakar, he introduced me to fonio, an ancient grain that is as easy as quinoa to cook and extremely tasty and nutritious. 
:
Photo 7 - Karelle Vignon-Vullierme and Olivier Vullierme are content creators of lifestyle and food content. Early in their relationship, Karelle started cooking for Olivier and decided to blog about her culinary adventures. What started out as a gesture of affection changed both their lives as they developed a following online!
:
Photo 8 - Malick Welli is a friend of mine and a Senegalese artist who has been working in photography and fashion for over a decade. While I was in Dakar, I was lucky enough to have a proper Senegalese meal with him and his friends of the BEST tasting thieboudienne (the national dish) I've ever had!
:
Photo 9 - I had a chance to dine with rapper Nix at La Favela. Born here in Dakar, Nix was raised speaking both French and Wolof. When he became a rap artist, it seemed natural to rap in French. But that started to feel like someone else’s language, so in 2016 he made a big change and switched to rapping in Wolof.
The spirit of TERANGA is felt deeply in Dakar ❤️🇸🇳 #LoveAfrica #Dakar #Senegal

A day in my Addis life: exploring Shola Market and learning about Ethiopian Coffee with Dr. Solomon Getaneh 🇪🇹 #AddisAbaba #Ethiopia #loveafrica

Addis Ababa is a city rich with history and culture.  As the capital of Africa’s only country NEVER to be colonized, there is an undeniable confidence to the energy of the place. Here are some of the wonderful people and places that left an impression on me:
:
Photo 2&3 - Shola is one of Addis’ larger open-air markets.  Lots of locally grown spices and grains can be found here. And, as I was walking through, I came across these guys playing foosball and I had to jump in - I lost miserably!
:
Photo 4 - Chef Yohanis Gebreyesus’ unique restaurant, Asabet features fish as part of every course of the meal - yes, including dessert!  His contemporary take on traditional recipes combines his passions for both food and art. I was lucky enough to have him teach me how to make his Ethiopian-style ravioli!
:
Photo 5 - Dr. Solomon Getaneh is a historian and theologian. We visited Kiddus Raguel (pictured here), the oldest church in Addis Ababa, and he also taught me a lot about the ancient vegan traditions in Ethiopia. Fun fact: traditionally, Ethiopians eat vegan for 250 days of the year! 
:
Photo 6 - Zertihun Guddisa is the manager of Selo Tella Bar. She was taught the craft of brewing the indigenous alcoholic beverage, tella, when she was 15, an art that is passed down by women in the family. Now she works at crafting commercial quantities of this Ethiopian beer, keeping the tradition alive and women employed. 

:
Photo 7&8 - I met hip hop artist Kassmasse at Shifta Foods. Kassmasse is one of the most influential Ethiopian artists right now and it was great to chat with him over some delicious African Caribbean-inspired vegan food!
:
Photo 9 & 10 - Meskerem Assegued is the visionary behind Zoma Contemporary Art Centre, a living museum where she has grown indigenous plants for the people to experience the natural potential of Ethiopia. The Center celebrates ancient techniques in art, architecture and food production. I was lucky enough to visit it, and it took my breath away.  These textured walls, for instance, are made of fermented mud and straw, and they can last hundreds of years. I highly recommend you check it out!
The sights, sounds and foods of Addis Ababa took my breath away! 🇪🇹 #LoveAfrica #AddisAbaba #Ethiopia

Thank you @abrimaerwiah and @studiooneeigehtynine for teaching me how to hand-batik! 🇬🇭 #LoveAfrica #Ghana #Accra

Ghana has a history of strong matrilineal lines and is paving the way for female-driven industry. I was lucky enough to spend some time in the capital city, Accra! Here are just a few amazing people I met along the way:
:
Photo 1 & 2: Before he died, Virgil Abloh was involved with the development of Ghana’s first Skatepark. Freedom Skatepark is the home of Skate Gal Club, which connects and empowers girls and women in Ghana through skateboarding. 👏🏿
:
Photo 3: This group is known as the Biker Girls GH and they come from all walks of life. I was so excited to ride with them!
:
Photo 4: Meet Kim Addison! 6 years ago, she moved from the US to Ghana with her sister, Priscilla, and they started ‘57 Chocolate, one of a few Ghanaian-owned chocolate brands. They commemorate a different Black revolutionary on the packaging of each flavor!
:
Photo 5: I attended a Ghanaian-style wine tasting with Ahaspora Young Professionals at Sai Wine & Champagne Café. Ghana’s first sommelier, Auntie Janet led us through the wine tasting. Owner Nadia Takyiwaa-Mensah told me that she opened the wine bar to introduce her fellow citizens to global wine culture with a focus on knowledge and empowerment.
:
Photo 6 & 7: At Studio 189, I hand-dyed fabric with owner, Abrima Erwiah and artisan, Agnes Arthur. It was fascinating to learn how they implemented local techniques into the process of production for their global brand!
:
Photo 8: I visited Makola Market with Esther Armah, an author, radio host and political commentator. It doesn’t get much busier than Accra's largest and most vibrant market, and the best part? It’s predominantly run by women!
:
Photo 9: Chef Maame Boakye is the owner of GHastro and it’s her passion to elevate traditional Ghanaian street foods to fine dining experiences. Her roasted corn, spread with mayonnaise and rolled in dried coconut: divine!
:
Photo 10: Peace Adjoa Fafa Sesi was my taxi driver when I left Accra, and you don't often see women driving taxis here. 14 years ago, Peace tried letting a guy handle her taxi business. He was unreliable and she was barely making money. So, what did she do? She said, "I'll handle this myself!"
Accra, the city of bada** women!! 🇬🇭 #LoveAfrica #Accra #Ghana

Rissois is delicious. Have you ever tried it? 🇲🇿 #Maputo #Mozambique #LoveAfrica

Maputo is one of the most beautiful cities in Africa. It’s an exciting place to be, with an energetic young population looking to the future. Here are some of the locals who left an impression on me:
:
Photo 2: Meet Osvaldo Cipriano, a talented architect who gave me a tour of the city and its most renowned architecture. Fun fact: until 1976 the city was called Lourenço Marques and when it gained independence after a 500 year Portuguese rule, it was given the name Maputo.
:
Photo 3: This is Ivan Muhambe of Maputo Street Art. During the pandemic, Ivan came up with an art walk of street art, creating a new tourist attraction.
Photo 4: Yara Chidiamassamba's love for sports led her to start volunteering at Favela United, where she shows young women how to defend their bodies, and build confidence through sports.
:
Photo 5: I joined Yara in the Favela United kitchen. The kitchen is run by community mothers like Dona Angelica, whose role is to look out for neighborhood kids and provide a meal to fuel the Favela United youth after games. On the menu for that day? Pão com Badjia, which I got to help make!
:
Photo 6: This is Mateus Sithole, a muralist who surprised me with this incredible portrait. During the pandemic, he developed a collage technique using strips of African print fabrics, extrapolating their dye to make artwork. The result is this textured tapestry. I was so moved by its inspired expression that it brought me to tears. Obrigado, Mateus!
:
Photo 7: (From L to R) Meet the owners and chef of Lumma, Maiane and Nadia Matavele and Chef Marcelino Dgedge. Chef Marcelino is preserving techniques and ingredients of Maputo food culture that have been used through the ages. The food at Lumma is ASTOUNDINGLY FLAVORFUL!
:
Photo 8: This is Witnei Shamusso, Fashion Designer and Creative Director of Wumburi. A few years ago, she struggled with her Mozambican identity, so she delved into past traditions and found her voice. Witnei designs Wumburis and aims to celebrate Mozambican women.
Photo 9: And finally, I had the most amazing time dancing with this Marrabenta dance troupe. Their energy was magnetic and I loved experiencing this expression of Mozambican culture!
Maputo is a wonderful city - have you ever been? It is so photogenic, colorful and warm.  Here are just a few things I love about it… 🇲🇿 #Maputo #Mozambique #LoveAfrica

I had an amazing time jumping with these incredible divers when I visited Zanzibar. Next time, head first!! 😜 🌊

In my visit to Zanzibar, I was overcome with the beauty and uniqueness of the island, the amazing flavors of the food and the wonderful people who live there. So many fascinating stories to share…

Meet Aiysha Mohammed (photo #2) my tour guide for the trip. She is the first female tour guide EVER in Zanzibar, a position she fought hard to achieve because of her fascination with the island’s history, culture and food. She is a trailblazer and hopes other women will follow in her footsteps.

These women (photo #3) are octopus hunters. It is an age-old practice on the island and has been revitalized in recent years.

This is Maida (photo #6). She is a musician, passionate about the traditional music of Zanzibar. Because of some conservative beliefs that still exist of what a female should do, she was unable to find someone to tutor her in violin, so she learned from YouTube! She now plays in a Taarab band and wants to share that tradition with the world.

This is Dr. Saidi (photo #7). He is passionate about the authentic history of this island and is a strong advocate for the culture and people from it.

And finally, meet Dr. Mwatima Juma and team. Dr. Juma’s passion project is organic farming, dedicated to putting Zanzibar on the organic farming map. I spent time with them at Msonge Organic Farm - one of the country’s organic farming success stories. Together, they are working on a delivery service that supplies fresh, organic, locally produced ingredients delivered to residents, hotels, and other businesses!

Have you ever experienced Zanzibar? It offers a truly unique and unforgettable experience.  Here's just a little taste of what I love about it… 🇹🇿 #zanzibar #LoveAfrica 

And thank you to all who welcomed me in Zanzibar. The octopus hunters who showed me their craft (and helped me with my hijab!), Dr. Mwatima Juma and team who showed me their passion for organic farming, Maida and her Taraab band who played the most wonderful music and Jamal and the rest of the divers, for showing me some fun!

Some moments at home in Nairobi to remember:

1. Home for me is family time. Shout-out to my Aunty Nyagoy for attempting to teach me how to make ugali, stewed fish and sukuma wiki, like my grandma's. And shout-out to the rest of the fam for eating it without complaint!
2. Freshly deep fried cassava crisps on the side of the road were an after-school delight for me growing up. Add a dash of salt, chilli and some lime - YUM!
3. Drinks at Beit e Selam restaurant with female tech entrepreneurs who are thriving in Nairobi! Meet them (left to right): Natalie and Samantha Mwedekeli (third from left) founders of Mama Rocks. Burgers aren't native to Kenya, but the flavor profiles they've created are homegrown for sure! Between them you’ll find my friend Sharon Olago, founder of Lishe Living, which helps shape healthy lifestyles. To my left is Nonnie Wanjihia Burbidge, an investment professional and founder of Try Cooked. And last, my cousin, Isis Nyong'o. Isis is a thought leader in the tech and media space and a Senior Advisor at ASG. These women rock!
4. The reason I am an actor is because of this fabulous woman to my right. My Aunty Amondi started me off performing in front of my family when I was 5 years old. She was my number one hype woman and still is. (Shout-out to my cousin Wema in the background. Love a family picnic!)
5. I found Chef Beni Rumasha on Twitter. He cooked me some scrumptious meals that tasted both familiar and new. His oxtail is not to be played with, and his gluten free chapatis were a hit with all!
6. I found Angela seated here de-kerneling a harvest of my grandmother's corn. She moved so swiftly, the corn seemed to glide off the cob. I had to try it, so I sat down to learn and help her…
7. My cousin Anam Bloch is a resourceful, dynamic and gifted young man. He is a talented music producer, determined not to be boxed into any genre. He also introduced me to the concept of aquaponic farming! He embodies the hustle of this vibrant city.
8. Aleya and Narmin Kassam gave us a chance to cook samosas for their business Wau Eats. I loved seeing how they adapted this Indian cuisine to embrace native ingredients and flavors.

I deeply love my mother. She is my closest friend and my number one champion. Today is her birthday. She was a baby once upon a time. She was a child once upon a time. I didn't know her back then (obvs!); when I met her when she was an adult, I thought she knew everything. Now that I am older, now that I am an adult myself, I know that she too is figuring things out as she goes through her one gifted life. 

But my mother has known a love that surpasses all understanding and she has shared it with us. She has taught me that the most rewarding thing to know, to pursue, is love. At a time when I am terrified to make that principle my north star, I am reassured by the bounty of her love and generous spirit. May I grow to be half the woman she is. #BirthdayTribute

Palmer is the kind of friend that I can count on through thick and very thin. We don’t have to talk every day, but when we do, we pick up exactly where we left off, like no time at all has passed. 

We were roommates in drama school and though we grew up in such different places (Kenya and Florida), we found a kindred spirit in each other, especially in the kitchen! We defied college norms and bought groceries together, we cooked for each other and carried the extra weight when one of us was too swamped with school work to do their fair share around the house. 

For Halloween, Palmer always looked out for me – one year she bought a bumble bee costume for herself at a dollar store and a ladybug costume for me because she knew I was not prepared to party that night! 

Recently, when my life was turned upside-down from heartbreak, Palmer flew in swiftly to be by my side and help me through the hardest days as I adjusted to my new reality. She made me delicious meals, she found me therapeutic activities to get my mind off things, she cried with me and made me laugh until I cried a more joyful kind of tear. She did not tire of being of service to me, and the biggest gift she bestowed on my life was helping me get my first pet, Yoyo. Now every time I look at him and cuddle with him, I am reminded of the selfless love my sister from another mister showed me. 

I will never be able to pay her back for the kindness she has shown me, and the beauty of the friendship is that it is never about evening the score! But I have every intention to try… Thank you truly, deeply, P! (Did I mention that she is also a kick-ass Tony Award nominated sound designer? Check out her latest work in PENELOPE!) @palmzhefferan #SunshineSeries

Remembering these three guardians on Dia de los Muertos. 

Rosemell Jane Achieng was my maternal grandmother. We called her Nyanya, but her children called her Honey. And that pet name rang true: she was sweet like honey and wrapped me up in warm hugs like honey wraps itself around your fingers. She would tell me stories and listen to my childish worries with patience and understanding. She loved to be entertained by her grandchildren. She marveled at our creativity and cheered us on for our small achievements. I stuck to her when she was around. She was taken from us too soon.

I remember my paternal grandmother, Dorca Owino Amolo, always bent over, working. She was never idle. She picked corn from her farm, kernelled it, dried it in the sun, sent it to be ground into flour in the local mill, and then cooked it into large mounds of delicious Ugali for the whole family to eat. She grew vegetables, raised livestock, and fermented her own milk. She swept, washed, brushed, scrubbed, chopped, stirred, pounded, and rolled. And she did all of this quietly, swiftly, gracefully, and with joy. Grandma taught me that work can be an expression of love, and I learned how to love the work of my body from her.

I had the honor of meeting one of my all-time heroes, Sidney Poitier, and I introduced him to my father. Mr. Poitier’s story and journey lit the path for me as an African coming to America to pursue a career in acting. He did the impossible and he did it with grace and dignity. When I met him, Mr. Poitier offered to take me to lunch the next time I was in town. It took me over a year to gather the courage to reach out and take him up on it, and I am so glad I did! They say don't meet your heroes because they may disappoint you; I dined with mine and gained even more respect and admiration for him than I had before!

Introducing my new companion, Yoyo!
I have historically been afraid of cats, but when my life was altered instantly recently, a little voice whispered to me that it was time to embrace change and new possibilities. So, a dear friend (shoutout Palmer Hefferan!) held my hand through the process and took me to visit my first animal shelters. I fostered Yoyo from Best Friends Adoption Center, and 3 days into it, I knew I could not give him up.
What I have learned about him already:
•  He LOVES company
•  He LOVES his food
•  He is extremely careful and rarely drops things
•  He is very picky about his wand toys
•  He only drinks running water
•  The bugs in the house don’t stand a chance
•  He can’t be trusted around supplements!
I never understood people whose phones were full of photos and videos of their pets - now I am one of those people! It may look like I saved Yoyo, but really, Yoyo is saving me. #YOYOYYO #Caturday 

And shoutout to the fantastic staff at @bestfriendsanimalsociety for being so warm, helpful and patient with me!

There are much more important things going on in the world right now, and my thoughts are with those who are deeply suffering.

At this moment, it is necessary for me to share a personal truth and publicly dissociate myself from someone I can no longer trust…

I find myself in a season of heartbreak because of a love suddenly and devastatingly extinguished by deception. I am tempted to run into the shadows and hide, only to return to the light when I have regained my strength enough for me to say, “Whatever, my life is better this way.” But I am reminded that the magnitude of the pain I am feeling is equal to the measure of my capacity for love. And so, I am choosing to face the pain, cultivating the courage to meet my life exactly as it is, and trusting that this too shall pass. The promise, they say, is that a tender heart is what gives birth to fearlessness. I hope it’s true… I share this to keep it 💯, and hoping that the knowledge of my experience might be useful to someone else out there experiencing the grip of heartbreak who is poised to try and escape from the pain and miss out on the wisdom that comes from it.  #Breakup

Let’s face our pain so we don’t spread it.

Dear Afro Hair,

From the depths of history to the heavens above, you embody resilience, beauty, and power. Each coil, kink, and curl carries the stories of ancestors, journeys, struggles, and triumphs. Your upward spirals defy limits, reflecting boundless strength.

Braided, loced, or free, your twists and turns are chapters in a heritage narrative, a symbol of rebellion and individuality. Despite adversity, you emerge stronger and more beautiful, a living testament to art, history, and poetry.

You’re not merely hair; you’re a badge of honor, a celebration of uniqueness. While the world may not fully grasp your splendor, those who wear, nurture, and adore you find inspiration. You epitomize raw beauty, nature’s creativity in tangible form.

Afro hair, you teach us to embrace every kink and curl, to revel in our distinctiveness. You stand as a symbol of our legacy and limitless potential.

With enduring admiration,

Vernon François

We didn’t want to strike, but now is the time to take ACTION. Inspired, fired up and united on the picket line with my fellow actors and writers this week. I know we stand on the right side of history for a more fair, secure and dignified livelihood for the many. #SAGAFTRAStrong #WGAStrong

Wondering why 160,000 @sagaftra actors are on strike? Here is an eye-level explanation from @chescaleigh with @msdanifernandez and @thenassersamara explaining what’s at stake 🙌🏿. The #SAGAftraStrike is in effect to support the rights of the thousands of actors (and writers in #WGAStrike) who are advocating for a more just, liveable system in our industry. This is not about getting the most, it’s about basic worker rights and transparently determining the fair value of the contributions of the many in accordance with the economic and technological changes of our times.

It’s a bad idea right???!! …

Let’s talk about intuition and when to say f-it and just have fun. Inner guidance is a tough one; one i question a LOT, but whether it’s with inner words or a gut feeling i cannot tell you how many times i look back and am like : why did i not listen?!
Buttt then there are other times when I think we are listening to the stories other people have told us that we have bought in to somehow, which are holding us back. Sometimes it’s okay to lean into having fun, as long as you’re actually having fun while doing whatever it is, and you’re not doing it because it’s serving another purpose coming from a place of insecurity. 
There is the work, and it’s done by asking yourself:
1. What do i want in this moment?
2. Is this going to truly make me feel good?
3. Am I and others safe doing it?
4. Can i live with any possible repercussions? 
5. And finally.. is this something I want for me.. or is this decision based on stories I’ve been told by other people?

G’luck ✨✨

Something that I’ve been practicing myself, is paying attention more; noticing. Seeing things in THIS moment, & really calling those things out for myself.. especially if I’m feeling a moment of stress or anxiety. It can be the most random of things, and I’ll do it mentally, in an appreciative way Ie. “I’m so appreciative to have this car to drive in right now,” (if I’m driving at that exact moment, )or “Wow, that’s a lovely green tree with beautiful purple flowers.” It may seem a bit silly to be calling out the obvious, but when we do this, we prevent our minds from going in a million different directions of thought (past, future, sads..) and we force ourselves to take whatever is stressing us out, and push it away, grounding ourselves in THIS moment. This gives us a moment of reprieve from thoughts of things that may never even happen, or our fears of things connected to whatever is actually happening. It’s called Being Mindful.. and it means that you pull your mind out of frantic thoughts, into calm Here and Now thoughts, which in turn, keeps you present, and grounded. It will then shift your energy juuuust enough for you to relax and allow your body to relax too, which in turn will make you vibrate at a higher level, and also make the problem or initial thought affect you just a little less. 💛
#energy #manifestation #feelinggood #illusion #illusions

When everything is a little upside down, inhale, exhale and ground yourself by saying 5 things you appreciate in the moment. Ie. I appreciate this coffee I’m drinking, I appreciate the sunny spot I’m sitting in.. etc. Bringing yourself into the present moment with something simple, that’s right in front of you, or that when you think of it, makes you feel good.. is the best way to realign yourself and raise your vibration. Raising your vibration and feeling good, is a fast track to manifesting things into your life 💛✨✨

#illusion #illusions #magic #manifestation #manifest #manifestationtips #howtomanifest #positivity #appreciation

I visited this Darca school while traveling in Israel, and the experience was epic. The kids are incredible; they’re talented and motivated, and it was really inspiring to see both Jewish and Arab students not just existing, but thriving together.

Here is a little more info about the Youth Renewal Fund and the Darca Schools Network: 

Youth Renewal Fund is the philanthropic and strategic funding partner for the Darca Schools Network in Israel. They work to build innovative education throughout Israel’s most underserved communities to improve social mobility. 

Darca is the #1 ranked educational network in Israel, providing Israeli high school students in lower-income communities with an excellent education — regardless of their ability, religion, birthplace, geographic or socioeconomic status. Darca currently operates 47 schools across 23 cities, serving over 27,000 students!

The alcohol industry, my personal journey with alcohol and some sexy statistics that’ll blow your mind. What’s not to love? 
Jokes aside, I am incredibly nervous to talk so publicly about my decision to stop drinking. I explain in this article why this feeling of shame around it is so common, with people either assuming you’re an alcoholic and choosing to look the other way, embarrassed but also a little angry that you’re suggesting that they should look at how much they drink. (Which you should.)
With lots of people beginning to talk about giving up alcohol - it felt like the right time and when I stumbled across @jomoclubofficial and the amazing ideas they have and are putting out into the world - it felt like the right time and place to open up. 
So this is a taste of my relationship with booze and my attempt to help others give up a drug that only takes and never gives. 
FULL article in the blog section on @jomoclubofficial website 🧡
Big love and happy rainy Monday.

Our teenage girls are in crisis, and we need to take urgent action. Join me?
 
There’s been a 75% rise in reports of vulnerable girls being exposed to bullying, grooming, domestic violence and child abuse and a shocking 94% increase in women and girls between 10-24 years old taking their own lives.
 
Girls Out Loud are a not-for-profit organisation that works with vulnerable teenage girls in schools by providing Big Sister mentors and professional youth coaching support to girls in desperate need of guidance and empowerment – their passion is to listen, guide and inspire them to make better choices, embrace their potential and know they are good enough.
 
This Christmas, I’m asking you to Help Save A Girl’s Life by donating to @girlsoutloudorg so that they can keep doing this vital work. YOU can make a HUGE difference to a girl’s life.
 
Please give what you can by following the link in my bio, follow their page and share this post to help spread the word.

So supposedly ear seeding—also called auricular acupressure—is a noninvasive treatment that stimulates pressure points on your ear with tiny seeds or beads. The goal of ear seeding is to alleviate specific symptoms or to improve your overall health… have you ever tried it before and what are your thoughts? 

I’m getting used to them. I can feel them in my ears and I keep wanting to touch them. But I also know I’d 100% pull them off if I did. So now I’m just lying in bed thinking about them sitting in there and trying not to think about them sitting in there.

Carbonara Deviled Eggs with @dorasticaviar FTW

6 eggs
8oz. pancetta
2 tbsp. parmesan 
Black pepper
Caviar
Chives 

Hard steam your eggs and set aside. 

In a pan over medium heat, cook pancetta until crispy. Reserve fat in a bowl and set pancetta aside. 

Cut eggs in half and scoop yolks into bowl with rendered fat, ground black pepper, and Parmesan. Mix until smooth and place in piping bag. 

To assemble, put crispy pancetta into egg whites. Pipe filling into egg and garnish with caviar, one pancetta bite, and chives. 

Enjoy!

Lahpet is Burmese for pickled or fermented tea leaves and not only is it a tasty national delicacy, it’s the key component of lahpet thoke or tea-leaf salad, a dish that if you ever come across it is well worth your time to try. San Francisco is home to several Burmese restaurants and Burma Superstar has been making this dish since 1992. 

In the late 1500’s and early 1600’s Buddhist monks helped lead a reform initiative to replace consumption of alcohol with fermented tea leaves in public ceremonies. Lahpet is considered a symbolic peace offering in ancient Myanmar.  It has a bittersweet and pungent taste and leafy texture. Many believe in its medicinal properties for the digestive system and it’s stimulant effect (from caffeine) makes it a popular snack for studying students and late night workers.

Inari Ōkami is the Japanese kami of foxes, fertility, rice, tea and sake, of agriculture and industry, of general prosperity and worldly success… the sweet fried tofu pouches that inari sushi a made with (also called kitsune) are given that name because they are lored to be either a favorite of foxes, or colored to resemble a fox. 

That said growing up as a Japanese American kid in LA - my family always called them “football sushi” and I honestly didn’t even know the name or the story about them until much later in life. It’s always fascinating to go down the rabbit hole and find out the things that shaped the foods we eat today.

#lactoseintolerant problems and I’ve got my answer… This (can be vegan if you use vegan pasta shells) creamed corn and lemon pasta was absolutely delicious and a new recipe I’m tucking in my back pocket for whenever I’ve got some cravings. 

1 1/2 cups pasta 
1 tbsp EVOO
4 cups corn kernels 
½ cup oat milk
2 tbsp nutritional yeast
1 lemon, zest and juice 
1 tbsp fresh thyme leaves
2 tsp red chili flakes
1/4 cup vegan Parmesan 
Salt & Pepper to taste 

Cook pasta and reserve 1 cup pasta water. 

In a pan, cook corn in olive oil with salt and pepper until browned or charred. Remove about half and put in blender with oat milk, nutritional yeast, and half the pasta water. Blend until smooth. Pour back into pan with pasta and add seasonings like thyme, chili flakes, and more salt and pepper. Cook for 5-8 minutes to thicken sauce. If the sauce gets too thick add more reserved pasta water to thin. Right before serving add Parmesan and melt into pasta sauce.

Yamaguchi Bonsai Nursery was established in 1949 by George Yamaguchi and his wife. The breathtaking private collection of bonsai on display there today can be attributed to his incredible artistry and lifetime of work. When George passed away in 2005, he left this established and community loved nursery as a legacy to his family. Today it is his daughter, Marianne, that carries on the tradition of excellence in plant selection and service. 

Giving a bonsai tree as a gift is a gesture of respect and a harbinger of good fortune. They symbolize harmony, honor, patience, as well as happiness among friends and family. 

And one more fun fact about this nursery is that they also offer bonsai babysitting and hospitalization services so for non green thumbs like me, Kale doesn’t have to worry about me killing Fred Deux. He can take him to Marianne for help!

Lutefisk is dried whitefish. Usually cod is used, but ling and burbot are also used. It is made from aged stockfish (air-dried whitefish), or dried and salted cod, cured in lye. The fish adopts a gelatinous texture after being rehydrated for days prior to eating.

Lutefisk is prepared as a seafood dish of several Nordic countries. 

Would you try it?

Apple pie 🥧 was always regarded as a symbol of American prosperity and since the 1800s, the thought of pairing fruits and cheese to aid in digestion was quite the fashion, so it only makes sense that these two items, cheddar cheese and apples, would find each other. The cheesy apple pie has been around, popular and polarizing for over a century and is absolutely an American classic that everyone should at least try once before making any untasted decries of “no way…” It surprisingly works. The sweet caramel crisp of apple pie filling with some nutty crunch is offset by the savory and creamy undertones of a good sharp cheddar. Plus with the buttery crust? Sign. Me. Up. 

(And yes I slightly over baked my pie topping… I got caught up in binging BEEF on Netflix and totally missed hearing my timer go off!)

Easter is around the corner and I’ve been craving donuts, so suit the occasion, this is my hot cross donut filled with @baileysofficial Original Irish Cream Liqueur and raisin custard and dusted with spiced sugar.
This is a brioche style donut, which gives the donut a softer and delicate texture!

90g milk
8g fresh yeast
30g beaten egg
50g dark brown sugar
2.5g salt
5g condensed milk
162g plain flour
30g unsalted butter

- combine ingredients together in a stand mixer and use a paddle to mix the ingredients together to a shaggy dough on medium speed.
- ⁠then change the paddle to a dough hook and work the dough until it becomes smooth and supple, scraping the bowl as you work the dough.
Then transfer dough onto a clean bench, and do the slap and fold 5-6 times until the dough is smooth, tight and taut. Then shape the dough into a ball and place into a lightly oiled bowl.
- ⁠proof the dough until double in size (45minutes)
- ⁠separate the dough to 50g balls and shape the individual doughs to rounds and place them onto parchment paper ready for a second proof (45minutes).

Meanwhile make the custard filling

2 yolks
250g milk
1 vanilla bean
25g sugar
20g cornstarch
70g raisins
90ml Baileys original (1.2 stnd drinks)

Scrape vanilla into the pot with milk and bring to a simmer. Meanwhile whisk yolks with sugar and corn flour.
Whisk in hot milk and discard the vanilla pods.
Return the mix to the pot and cook over medium heat while whisking until custard thickens.
Whisk in baileys and raisins.
Transfer to a piping bag and leave in the fridge to cool.

Spiced sugar:
200g icing sugar
1tbs ground cinnamon
1/2 tsp ground all spice
1/4 tsp ground nutmeg

Whisk together in a bowl.

Heat fryer to 190C and fry proofed donuts for 2-3minutes until golden brown, then flip to cook the otherside.
Allow to cool.

Once cooled, toss in spiced sugar and poke a hole in the side of the donut and fill with the baileys raisin custard.

Pipe melted white chocolate on top to make the cross for the donuts.

This is my super refreshing dessert ‘Limed Up’ spiked with the smooth PATRÓN EL CIELO Tequila.

A take on a boozy Brazilian limeade turned into a sorbet and served with a pineapple mint compote inside a fresh lime, topped with milk tuile, meringue, zest of lime and a dust of dried mint.

It’s so good I’ve got to put this on my menu next. 

Limeade Sorbet:
4 Tahitian limes
1Lt Water
1 can Sweetened condensed milk
75g Stabiliser - sorbet
65g Caster sugar
120ml PATRÓN EL CIELO

Blend lime, water, condensed milk together and strain then blend in the stabiliser, sugar and tequila. Churn in an ice cream machine and set aside in the freezer.

Pineapple Mint Compote:
100g Pineapples, diced
200g Pineapple juice
2g Agar
10 Leaves of mint, finely chopped

Whisk agar with pineapple juice and bring to a boil, then pour mixture into a container and leave in fridge to set. Once set, blend to a smooth gel and mix in the diced pineapples and mint.

Lime Cup:
Fresh Lime

Cut 2cm from the top of the lime, set aside for later use.
Remove the inside pulp of the lime by using a small knife, scissors and spoon, carefully cutting within the pith without piercing through the skin.
Store in a container in the fridge.
Keep the pulp aside and juice for future limeade mix.

To serve:
Fill lime cups half way with pineapple mint compote and then transfer the sorbet into a piping bag with a star nozzle and pipe into the lime cups to create a soft serve swirl effect.
Garnish with dried milk crisps and meringue, finish with zest of lime from the lime tops and dust of freeze dried mint powder.
Serve on a bed of crushed ice.

Check out this cool cocktail for you to try this Summer using T2 Iced Watermelon Fiesta, it’s a gin base cocktail with a frozen yogurt foam and compressed watermelon.
 
You can replicate this recipe at home without the fancy items too! I just wanted to be a little bit extra.
 
This drink is so fresh and fun, I wanted to layer it in a way that represents the colour gradient of a watermelon. Perfect for a hot day or… any day really!
 
Serves 2
 
Yogurt foam:
70g Plain yogurt
1/2 Lime juice + zest
35g Sugar
50g Cream
30g Milk
 
[Easy-level] Whisk everything together
[Pro-level] place everything in a siphon and charge with nitrous oxide.
[Extra pro-level] siphon into a bath of nitrogen and crush into small pieces.
 
Drink:
40ml Dry gin
30ml Elderflower liqueur
40ml Rose simple syrup
200ml T2 iced watermelon fiesta
 
• shake ingredients together with some ice and pour into a glass.
 
Watermelon Garnish:
Watermelons cut into small wedges
Splash of yuzushu
 
[Easy-level] Combine wedges and yuzushu together in a container and allow to marinate
[Pro-level]: Compress watermelon with yuzushu in vacuum chamber
 
Place yogurt on top of the drink and garnish with a side of watermelon and dust with some english mint powder.

I just came back from Japan and if you know me well enough, you know I love my mochi ice creams... It’s a guilty pleasure of mine. 
I was in a snacking mood today, so I also lost count on how many I ate whilst filming this recipe.
•
This is the Ice Cream Daifuku with Connoisseur’s Matcha White Chocolate and Strawberry Jam.

Mochi Dough:
100g Sweet glutinous rice flour
30g Cornflour
6g Matcha powder
55g Caster sugar
180g Milk
15g Unsalted butter
extra cornflour for dusting

- combine the dry ingredients together and whisk, then whisk in the milk until a smoothe paste is formed.
- cover with cling film and puncture with holes. 
- microwave on high for 1 minute, then at 30second bursts until dough is formed. 
- Add in the butter and use a rubber spatula to mix well into the mochi dough.
- knead the dough and stretch with gloved hands.
- dust work surface with cornflour and portion into smaller pieces. 
- dust the mochi well and roll into desired thickness and shape

Strawberry jam
Matcha powder
Connoisseur Matcha White Chocolate

- Lay the mochi sheet over a small cup or bowl to hold and scoop in the ice cream and add in strawberry jam to switch things up too (I did both).
- Wrap the edges together and pinch tight to seal. Store in freezer until ready to devour!

Bring a little festive magic with this delicious dessert, perfect to end the meal on a Summer Christmas night.

This is the Summer Snow. 

-

Snowball:

Connoisseur Classic Vanilla 
Dessiccated Coconut

Scoop out the ice cream and roll it in the coconut, place on a tray and keep in the freezer. It’s okay if the shape isn’t perfect.

Cherry Compote:

250g Cherries, pitted
50g Caster Sugar
Half juice of lime

Place all ingredients in a pot and cook over medium heat until consistency thickens. Set aside to cool.

Swiss Meringue:

125g Egg Whites
250g Caster Sugar

Whisk sugar and whites over a baine marie until sugars are dissolved, then whip to stiff peak with standmixer until cooled down.

Transfer to a piping bag.

Pipe a dollop of the meringue onto the plate and using the back of the spoon, create a well for the cherry compote. 

Then add some cherries and grated lime zest. 

Take snowballs out of the freezer and shape again to a nicer ball and place on top of the cherry.

Heat up some rum or kirsch with a blow torch or gently over the stove (low heat) until it lights up.

Carefully spoon the flambéd liquor around the meringue and enjoy the magic.

#ad I love a tiramisu and when @baileysofficial Limited Edition Tiramisu Flavoured Liqueur launched, I had the idea to add it into my go-to tiramisu recipe for double the flavour.
Here is my lamington inspired tiramisu with toasted coconut, sponge and chocolate glaze. Simple and delicious, just as a tiramisu should be.

Try it at home, and feel free to get creative with how you construct it. No matter how you build it, it’ll taste amazing. Give it a go, recipe’s below!

Sponge cake
5 Egg yolks
150g Sugar
5 Egg whites
50g Sugar
125g Plain flour
2g Baking powder
1 Vanilla bean
85g Full cream milk

Preheat oven to 170C.
Whip whites with 50g of sugar until stiff peak. Then whip yolks with 150g sugar and vanilla until pale. Whisk in milk to yolks and sift in flour with baking powder, fold until smooth. Then fold in whites and spread onto a lined flat baking tray. Bake for 17minutes, then allow to cool before cutting to 4x4cm squares.

Mousse
5 Egg yolk
75g Sugar
1 Vanilla
140g Baileys Limited Edition Tiramisu Flavoured Liqueur
1 Gelatine
500g Mascarpone cheese
100g Cream
80g Sugar
2 Egg whites

Soak gelatine in cold water until soft.
Meanwhile whisk sugar, vanilla with yolk over a water bath until pale and add gelatine. Then add the Baileys Tiramisu Flavoured Liqueur.
Then whisk egg whites with sugar until fluffy.
Whip mascarpone and cream to soft peak and whisk into the yolks and then fold in the whites

Coffee soak
4 Espresso shots
50g Marsala
30g Coffee liqueur

Mix ingredients together well and pour onto a small tray or container.
Soak both sides of sponge squares.
Pipe 1/4 of mousse into square silicone mould (5x5cm) then a layer of soaked sponge on top. Repeat until it is filled to the top and freeze until solid.

Glaze
500g Water
250g Sugar
8 Gelatine titanium
100g Condensed milk
150g Cocoa powder
60g Glucose

Soak gelatine in cold water until softened.
Meanwhile combine all ingredients together and cook over low heat until 80C, then whisk in gelatine. Pass through a strainer and allow to cool to 30C before pouring over the frozen tiramisu cake.

Garnish with toasted desiccated coconut and gold.

#Baileys #BaileysTiramisu #Tiramisu #Lamington #drinkresponsibly

Here’s something fun and easy you can do with Connoisseur Ice Cream's newest flavour - Jam Doughnut! 

 

This is the ‘not not a doughnut’ - I reshaped the ice cream into the shape of a doughnut and dipped it in a white chocolate coating with berries! Fun and delicious to share around this festive season.

You’ll need a very cold freezer that goes to -28C or -30C.
200g White chocolate
200g Cocoa butter or Coconut oil
20g Freeze dried blackberry and raspberry (found in farmers markets, online or specialty stores) 

Paddle ice cream in a mixer then pipe onto a cold tray lined with baking paper. Transfer ice cream into a piping bag with a large round nozzle and work quickly to pipe ice cream into doughnut rounds. Leave in the freezer until firm, then flip the ice cream upside down and pipe again on the flat side. Keep in the freezer until needed.

Meanwhile melt chocolate and cocoa butter together and mix in crushed freeze dried berries.

Then using gloves, shape the ice cream doughnuts and tidy the sides with your hands.
Finally, use two skewers to dip them into the chocolate mix.

A gently cooked cod is probably my favourite way to enjoy the fish.
This blue eye cod has been drying for 3-4 days before getting carved and is then brined in a 6% solution for 1 hour. 
The bones then gets roasted and turned into a thick bone broth stock for the velouté sauce.
The loin is used for this dish, belly and tail gets used for our snack courses and excess parts of skin, bone, head also gets used to create a fragrant oil infusion. 

Here the cod is rolled and gently poached, paired with some beautiful white asparagus, bone veloute, leek oil and desert limes.
Just to switch things up - best enjoyed with a non-alcoholic wine @non.world NON 3 - toasted cinnamon and yuzu which pairs nicely with delicate seafood.
If you’re looking for some non-alcoholic wines, I highly recommend you try NON.

Preparing a new marron course for tonight’s private dinner for my friends.
They come often, so it puts a little pressure for me to make something new. 
This one was quite an epic dish. 
Poached and bbq’d marron with red curry using some native spices with the blend. 
Added some coconut cream to the curry when cooking and strained, reduced, seasoned with lime, salt, sugar. Then emulsified together with a pinch of xanthan.
Served with some beach herbs (sea blight, samphire, karkalla) desert lime, yuzu and shell oil. 
You don’t see the claws here being used in this dish but I added that onto a previous course which is the chawanmushi.
I love how the marron can be used across multiple dishes and must say it’s my favourite crayfish. 
100% shits on lobsters imo 🤷🏻‍♂️.

Last year when we first opened in April 2022 I had a dish called ‘Floral’ - consisted of feijoa, orange blossom, yogurt, myrtle and yuzu.

This here is layered from the bottom with an earl grey cremeux then a snow of elderflower sake on one side and strawberry on the other.
Topped in the center with a scoop of lychee sorbet, covered with a raspberry tuile and a touch of yuzu gel with flowers.

/paspaley
A stunningly interesting dish that celebrates the pearl. Where the pearl is made of a salted walnut and kombu cream coated in a thin cocoa butter shell. Raw slices of pearl meat, a firm meaty texture than that of a scallop with a delicate sweet and saltiness. Served with a dollop of gold oscietra reserve caviar and warmed creme fraiche and chive oil. All plated on a mother of pearl shell. 

The irish moss seaweed is soaked with warm water and placed as a bed for the dish. Nitrogen is then poured to give not only a visial effect but the fog carries the scent of the ocean from the seaweed.
Quite pleased with this dish, visually stunning, unique and most importantly it tastes great.

🌼I’ve been really into cocktails as of late and thinking of making a series of reels where I turn my desserts into cocktails. 
The two always go hand in hand with pairing and mixology is just as much as cooking involved with liquids as it’s core. 
Here’s Yellow from @koiexperiential /phase 3. A milk washed punch, I’m not really sure what I’m doing but it was a refreshing and fragrant drink.

- Whay do you think, should I turn my desserts into drinkable delectables?

Yellow:
20 Jasmine tea simple syrup
Lime zest
30 tequila reprosada 
20 dark double aged rum
30 calamansi juice
20 mango puree 
150 milk
- strain through a filter.

Ice
20 lychee liqueur
70 milk washed punch

Shake.

Then I garnished it with our Sunflower mango with frozen lychee.

TV shows are the stories we bring into our homes. They shape how we understand the world, each other, and our place in it.

The latest study from @inclusionists reminds us that when it comes to Muslim portrayals, we’re still being fed a TV diet of stereotyping and erasure.

For Muslims this sends a message that they don’t belong or don’t matter. For other people, we risk normalising fear, bigotry and stigmatisation against Muslims.

Networks and streaming services need to embrace their responsibility to ensure Muslims of all backgrounds see themselves reflected in our favourite TV shows and seize this gigantic opportunity to connect with an underserved global audience - not just as part of a passing diversity fad but as a decisive shift towards inclusive story-telling.

Check out TheMuslimBlueprint.org to learn more.

Big thanks to @inclusionists for the data, @monachalabi for the illustrations, and @pillarsfund and @fordfoundation for their support. Proud to launch this with my team at Left Handed Films.

#TheMuslimBlueprint

When you spend your life code switching you learn to never bring all of your raw, unfiltered self to the table. But this film was just that - our families and fears, the music and the message, Urdu and English - holding nothing back. Winning an Oscar for THIS film of all films? It’s a lesson to make the thing you think you shouldn’t.

Also, Oscar’s are seriously heavy. Carrying one for 12 hours feels like your shoulder is dislocating. And maybe that was a lesson too - that the weight you carry is the reward, the pain is the poetry, your gift and curse are the same. Confront your adversity, embrace it, and share it - it will elevate you. That’s what we did with this film. We put our nightmares on screen and they turned into a dream. 

Thank you God for teaching me. 

Shout out to everyone who has helped carry that weight as we made this film - @_aneil_ you are a genius and one of the great filmmakers of your generation, @redinho808 your music was the backbone of this film and album,  @carolinereason you’re my sister and have been holding me on this journey for so long thank you, @astridferguson you’re a G and there’s seriously nothing you can’t do, @djbradfield you’re an artist’s dream and @wepresent @somesuchandco @randcpmk @londonflairpr @elevenmgmt we wouldn’t be here without you. 

Thank you to my family and to my wife @ffmirza for being my torch in the darkness.

On behalf of myself and Left Handed Films, thank you to the Academy for recognising ‘The Long Goodbye’ for best live action short film, and honouring ‘Flee’ with a historic 3 nominations for Best Animation, Best Doc, and Best Intl Feature! 

It’s an amazing feeling to be here just one year into creating Left Handed Films. These are two deeply personal and urgent stories that are totally unique in their creative execution, and so close to our hearts. That’s the kind of work we want to make.

Wow! I'm honoured to be nominated by my fellow actors alongside such inspiring performances, and am grateful to the Academy for their support and encouragement. I’m equally thrilled for our visionary writer-director Darius Marder and the brilliant Paul Raci, as well as our editor Mikkel, sound designer Nicolas, and co-writer Abe Marder. These nominations represents the time, generosity and talents of so many — all of our incredible cast, crew, producers, and in particular I’d like to thank my mentors in the drumming, addiction recovery, and D/deaf communities.⁣
⁣
Sound of Metal is about how a health crisis can cut you off from your life and loved ones, and force you to grow in unexpected ways. In a challenging year for so many, I hope this story can inspire us to forge new and deeper connections with ourselves and others.

Hi! My name is Jeremy Lee Stone, and I’m taking over Riz’s Instagram account to share my experience as an actor in our new film #SoundofMetal, now on @amazonprimevideo . For those who don’t know me, I’m a Deaf advocate and ASL coach.
 
As a member of the Deaf community, I find themes of collaboration, sharing of information, loyalty, sensitivity, protectiveness, and an authentic collective to be some of our strongest attributes. And the Deaf community is one that welcomes anyone who learns the language as communication, in any form, builds human connection.
 
So it was a pleasure to teach Riz American Sign Language and bring him into the NYC Deaf community. Riz has the recognition in this industry that has been a platform to shed light on many things. One of which being hearing loss, which can affect anyone and lead to a true lifestyle change. It also has brought to the forefront the 3rd most used language across America — ASL. Lastly, I feel that he has helped to showcase Deaf and HoH Talent through this medium. It was great to see him strip his identity, his reputation and just exist in this world of ASL.
 
There may be some misunderstandings out there that Sound of Metal is a film about the Deaf community. Rather, it is a film of one man's journey through hearing loss and how he is welcomed into the Deaf community. As just one member of that community, I cannot state what Deaf audiences will feel while watching this film, but I do feel it's a story of finding one's identity.  That is a theme that many can resonate with.
 
And being a part of Sound of Metal was a wonderful opportunity to see diverse Deaf Talent on screen. This has been an important movement towards more representation. Let Riz and I know what you think of the film, and you can follow me @jeremy.lee.stone 
 
#ASL
#DeafCommunity
#deaf

#Soundofmetal was the most intense & rewarding creative experience of my life. Connecting with people I wouldn’t have otherwise, and connecting more deeply than ever with myself. I hope it connects with you. 🙏🏽

Oh Bibi, how you will be missed, from greeting me after school to sneaking chocolate without mom knowing. You were so beautiful. You made the funniest jokes that made us all laugh, and your smile lightened and room you walked in. I loved that we would make up funny words that only we could understand. You were one of the BEST grandmas ever. I can’t express my sadness, but deep inside I keep telling myself I know your in a better place. I can’t get this through my mind and I keep on thinking I’m living in a nightmare I just can’t wake up from. Oh and how you loved chocolate, how you would come in my room and ask for candy. You had one of the biggest sweet tooth ever!  I know you were having trouble breathing but now your in a better place. I loved how much you loved getting dressed up and fancy, and oh how you loved that cat. Peeshi was your favorite cat ever. That was Cameron’s gift to you for Christmas after you lost your beloved Tubby, now you are with him. We are all going to miss you so so so so very much and we will never ever forget you. 
With love, Sofia
